A bone house fascinates even after 100 years. Look at the interiors of Gaudi
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric ech, the stairs like the spine of a dinosaur and the balconies are torn-up fish mowers.
This is Casa Batlló of Catalan architect Antonio Gaudi in Barcelona.
Of the local inhabitants, the house with its organic forms was nicknamed \"Knochenhaus\"
Organic shapes, wild colors, the unusual use of stone, tile splits and mosaics, which resemble shuffling facades and omnipresent soft lines, all these are typical features for Antonio Gaudi's youth style.
The façade of the house plays with fantastic lines, tender colors and textures that remind us of nature and living beings.
It is only when we look more closely at it that everything is dominated by geometry, rhythm and thought-in order.
During the night, the entire facade still seems more plastic, dramatic and the special illumination enhances the shine of the colors.
The same swivel lines and curved shapes also dominate the interior of the house.
Wave-shaped wood copies the window frames, fences, ornamental elements of doors, even guckholes and lashes.
The house Batlló in the Eixample district on the lively shopping street Passeig de Grácia No. 43 was constructed by the conversion of a house from 1877, which was performed by the architect Emilio Sala Cortese.
The reconstruction took two years and was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Joseph Batlló, originally insisted on the demolition of the old and the construction of a completely new building, but ultimately he agreed to the idea of Gaudí for an unusual and even cheaper conversion.
However, Casa Batlló's rental house did not design Antoni Gaudí alone.
He worked with the architect Joseph Maria Jujol.
The decorations for the representative home of the real estate owner and also the use of mosaics on the facade were his idea.
However, many other artists and artists also worked on the design of the façade.
The joint work on the drafts for Casa Batlló was the start of a fruitful cooperation between Jujola and Gaudí.
Jujol also participated in the construction of Gaudí's Casa Milá house in the Park Güell, in which further works of Antoni Gaudí are also located.
Shortly after its completion, the house got from the local inhabitants of its organic forms due to the nickname \"Knochenhaus\"
Others, in turn, called it the special window opening mechanism because of the \"likening house\"
It is also said that at the top of the building is the sword of St. George, the patron of Catalonia.
But also other pictorial elements symbolize hidden religious motives.
Gaudí designed for the house a unique central heating system with ventilating channels and typical fireplaces for that time.
It's a bit bizarre that their 45-degree inclination is already on.
In his work, Gaudí consistently ignored all the building regulations at that time and could by no means interfere with them.
Before the construction began, he had obtained from the city the corresponding construction permit, but the information he made about the planned reconstruction was so vague that two years later, the city fathers were so displeased with the result that they requested relief.
The councillors also insisted, among other things, that the construction with its pillars even intervened in public citizenship.
However, no further changes were made, on the contrary - only fifteen days after the call to the city district in question, Joseph Batlló made an application to approve the renting of the two highest floors of the house - and she was promptly granted it.
The owner himself moved into the lower floors.
In the gallery on the 2nd floor was a company salon, on the third floor were the bedrooms and private rooms of the apartment.
The ground floor was engaged in a jeweling business.
The entire six-storey building runs through a staircase up to the roof terrace.
Due to the basic elements of the conversion, all right angles and straight lines were removed and replaced by curved and curved walls.
Gaudí, however, also worked with a modern concept for connecting rooms.
The social part can be completely connected by opening the salon doors and thus a larger society could easily chat without having to give up some intimacy in more confidential conversations.
The house was also given a rather unusual roof and two more floors by Gaudí's conversion except for a new façade.
Amazing is Gaudí's game with the light as well as the blue and white glazed tiles with which the courtyard is dressed and the lighthouses.
The game of these two colors gives all the floors of the house a maximum amount of light.
In doing so, he simply made the principle of utility that white reflects the light better than dark colors that absorb sunlight on the contrary.
The Casa Batlló House, which was included in the Unesco World Heritage List in 2005, can visit anyone today.
On the first floor, the most spacious and magnificent apartment is made accessible to the public.
The owners of the house only decided in the year to this step and this on the occasion of the 150th birthday of the famous creator.
When it was found that this is a fairly attractive business, the visits were maintained, but it was extended to other common and the rooftop rooms, including the rooftop terrace.
However, the price of visiting the building monument is not a pop-up steel, it is 16.50 Euros, students, pensioners, groups and owners of tourist certificates get 20 percent discount.
This amount exceeds the entry prices for other Gaudí buildings in the city.
If you want to get to know the real atmosphere of the house with its dragon towers, try to make friends with one of the householders and visit him at home.
