A longer index finger than a ring finger means a lower risk of cancer
Men whose index finger is longer than the ring finger are obviously at a lower risk of developing prostate cancer.
This is the surprising result of a study published by the British Journal of Cancer on Wednesday.
This should be related to the mirror of the male hormone testosterone.
“Our results show that the relative length of fingers can serve as a simple test for the risk of prostate cancer, and this is especially for men up to sixty - explained the co-author of the study, Ros Eeles, professor at the Cancer Research Institute at the University of Warwick.
The finger could help determine which men should necessarily undergo a prostate cancer test, especially if there are genetic risks or other risk factors, such as family health risks, added Ms. Eeles.
During the period 1994-2009 she and her colleagues in Britain followed more than 1500 patients with prostate cancer, but also 3000 healthy men.
In more than half of the study participants, the right hand index finger was shorter than the ring finger.
For these men, the same probability of prostate cancer as for 19 percent of those men whose ring and index fingers were equally long.
However, in men whose index finger was longer than the ring finger, this risk decreased by 33 percent, in men up to sixty by 87 percent.
