Sport and regulation
Tricks like those of Alonso and Ramos in the game against the Ajax show invention spirit, but not the will to circumvent a sanction.
The alleged exclusion in the game of November 23 against the Ajax in the Champions League led to a lot of ink being shed on whether it was an unsportsman action or not and whether perhaps both players should be sanctioned by the UEFA.
As is commonly known, the two players lost a few minutes before playing (their team had already clearly won) time and played several fouls so that the judge showed them the second yellow card.
In this way, and since Real Madrid would lead its group, the two players will meet the prescribed penalty at the next league game against the Auxerre and thus enter the next game without any cards.
Finally, UEFA's disciplinary committee punished the club's coach José Mourinho, with two games and the players involved with different amounts of money.
The provocation of a yellow card under such or similar circumstances is not a new practice, it is more common in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos - the unwritten, but in this sport followed rules.
Part of the debate about the case presented goes back to the fact that a team of the Real Madrid football club (who pretends to be noble and honorable in his hymn and had punished his players for similar incidents on other occasions) played the main role, and to the dramatization by Mourinho, who added an episode more to his long history as a theatrical and provocation technician.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether it does not explicitly contradict the principles of sport, that is, whether these acts constitute a rule of conduct. In fact, this procedure adheres to the statutes of sport, but seems to circumvent its meaning.
In this matter, the damage caused by the spirit of sports should be examined.
The sports spirit defends the physical integrity of the opponents, an aspect that was not endangered by these actions because it was not an aggressive game.
Another aspect of a clean game is to avoid the opponents from taking an unjustified advantage from the counter-team. Neither did it happen.
The paradox of the action of the Real Madrid players is that it does not correspond to what we normally understand under false play or rule, because the circumvention of the rule was not carried out secretly to avoid a penalty, but it should be as obvious as possible so that it is punished by the arbitrator.
The players waited and gladly accepted the penalty.
Another question is what kind of advantage the offenders draw from the deliberate fouls.
It should be stressed here that the rival was neither brought into a more unfavorable position nor increased benefits for the game played, because the obvious result of this action was that the own team had to continue playing with fewer players.
It is also not a useful strategy for the next game, because the club then does not have these players.
The advantage is obviously that the players start the next game phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future game.
But it is a long-term, up to a certain degree uncertain advantage, as the team might eventually get out. Furthermore, the players receive a penalty with this procedure and pass into the second card cycle, in which they opt out with a card less than in the first cycle due to accumulation of cards.
So it is not so clear whether it really is an advantage.
In the end, such practices do not contradict the spirit of sport, which also includes strategic decisions in order to make the greatest possible use of the rules.
In this case, the players did not want to commit any penalty (which would actually be a clear case of rule circumvention), they wanted to choose when they were subject to it.
They made a strategic decision to escape or escape without a penalty.
Although the boundary between invention and regulatory environment is blurred, I believe that this is a clear case of invention.
I have the impression that the polemics arose as a result of two factors: because it was about two self-exclusions and because of the nature of the provoked rule transmission.
The damage inflicted on the principles of sport by these actions is less ethical than rather aesthetic.
