Global plan for the renewal of lighting
Yesterday in Cancun, the UN has proposed a plan to renew the lighting of households, trade and industry in 100 countries in order to achieve a reduction in greenhouse gas (FCKW), which corresponds to nearly one third of the additional reduction that needs to be realized in order to stabilize the Earth's climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan takes its position in the steps of concrete major projects that the UN hopes to implement in Cancun in order to compensate for the absence of mandatory reduction commitments by the industrialized countries.
According to the plan presented yesterday, the main problem would be avoided in the form of the 1.8 billion tonnes (Gt) of the FCKW issued on the ground due to lighting if the white-flowering pears, which are still a 50 to 70% monopoly on the market, would be replaced by fluorescent or better, LEDs.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This corresponds to an equivalent of 70% of the exhaust gases of the global fleet.
Last year, in Copenhagen, the major exhaust emitters, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed themselves to voluntary reduction plans to cut global FCKW emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
However, it was necessary to withdraw 5 Gt from this balance sheet in order to stabilize the climate increase by 2 degrees Celsius from today to 2020 in order to prevent this from being out of control.
In the white-glossed pears, 95% of the energy escapes in the form of heat, and the remaining 5% produce the light.
With the compact light bulbs, energy consumption decreases by 75%, with the new LED bulbs, this energy requirement is again reduced by twofold.
The compact light bulbs keep on average between 6000 and 10,000 hours.
The new LED bulbs, such as those brought to the market by the manufacturer Philips this week - this company, by the way, has participated in the UN study - have a life expectancy of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than a white bulb, which gives an indication of the savings possibilities of the exchange plan to be applied in 100 countries.
In addition to the fact that your completely new bulbs give off very little heat, they can also work with a rule resistance.
And they do not contain any mercury.
Several specialists have indicated that compact light bulbs have reserves, as they contain mercury and therefore have to be disposed of as special waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, except the producers provide an acceptance body.
However, according to the report, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not the compact light bulbs, but rather the coal power plants, which emit much more mercury to produce the electricity wasted by the white-glossed pears.
In the United States alone, these coal power plants emit 25,000 tonnes of mercury annually.
The report details the profits that each country would generate thanks to this international programme.
Indonesia, for example, would save one billion dollars annually in the purchase of electricity and eight million tons of CO2, which means an equivalent of 3.5 coal power plants, the construction of which would cost 2.5 billion.
